In Spring Boot, Spring Profiles are used to manage different configurations for different environments.

Example environments:

Development
Testing
Production

Each environment can have different database settings, ports, or properties.

Why Spring Profiles Are Used

Suppose your application runs in:

Environment	Database
Development	H2
Testing	MySQL
Production	Oracle

Instead of changing application.properties every time, we use profiles.

1️⃣ Profile-Specific Property Files

Spring Boot allows separate configuration files.

Example:

application-dev.properties
application-test.properties
application-prod.properties
Example
application.properties
spring.profiles.active=dev
application-dev.properties
server.port=8081
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
application-test.properties
server.port=8082
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/testdb
application-prod.properties
server.port=8083
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@localhost:1521:xe
2️⃣ Activating a Profile

In application.properties:

spring.profiles.active=dev

or from command line:

--spring.profiles.active=prod
3️⃣ Using @Profile Annotation

We can also activate beans based on profiles.

@Configuration
@Profile("dev")
public class DevConfig {

}

This configuration will run only in dev profile.

Example Flow
Application Start
       ↓
Spring reads active profile
       ↓
Loads corresponding properties
       ↓
Runs application with that configuration
Advantages
Advantage	Explanation
Environment separation	dev/test/prod configs
Easy configuration	no manual changes
Cleaner project	organized properties
